  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
      "identifier": "config_runtime_context_rmw_update_loss",
      "summary": "Config runtime context setters are separate read-modify-write operations on a shared atomic pointer, which can drop updates under concurrent or interleaved calls.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/config/config.go",
        "goseg/startuporchestrator/startup_orchestrator.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`setRuntimeContextBasePath`, `setRuntimeContextDebugMode`, and peers all load `RuntimeContextSnapshot()`, mutate one field, then store the updated struct.",
        "Because each setter writes the full struct independently, concurrent callers can overwrite unrelated fields (for example, basePath and architecture) with stale snapshots.",
        "Multiple tests and call sites mutate runtime context via these setters (for example `SetBasePath`, `SetDebugMode`) indicating this path is part of runtime dependency control, not a single-threaded one-off initialization."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Refactor runtime-context updates to serialize through a single `updateRuntimeContext` helper (mutex-protected or CAS loop) that applies a full mutate function to the current snapshot, then stores once; keep public setters as thin wrappers over that shared updater.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "single_edit",
      "root_cause_cluster": "function_seam_mutability_race"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
      "identifier": "wireguard_recovery_seam_lacks_contract_guards",
      "summary": "Wireguard recovery uses a function-field seam without validation, creating an abstraction that can be instantiated in an invalid state and panic at runtime.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/shipworkflow/recovery.go",
        "goseg/shipworkflow/recovery_test.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`RecoverWireguardFleet` accepts `wireguardRecoveryRuntime` directly and immediately calls `runtime.GetShipStatusFn`, `RestartContainerFn`, `WaitForShipExitFn`, etc. without nil checks.",
        "The function type is exported via `NewWireguardRecoveryRuntime`, but callers can bypass it with a zero-value or partially filled struct because the public entry point does not enforce required seams.",
        "Other runtime compositions in this batch (for example workflow/runtime constructors) validate callback groups before use, while this seam has no comparable guard."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Introduce a runtime validator for wireguard recovery (required callback set) and change `RecoverWireguardFleet` to obtain runtime via a constructor that returns an error on missing callbacks, or perform explicit nil checks at entry.",
      "confidence": "medium",
      "impact_scope": "module",
      "fix_scope": "single_edit",
      "root_cause_cluster": "function_seam_mutability_race"
    }
  ],
  "retrospective": {
    "root_causes": [
      "Runtime abstractions are defined as mutable shared state or raw function buckets without a single, enforced contract boundary.",
      "Context mutation APIs expose split-field writes instead of transactional updates."
    ],
    "likely_symptoms": [
      "Intermittent loss of runtime context values when multiple set operations run in close sequence",
      "Potential nil-function panics in recovery paths if a seam runtime is misconstructed outside the default constructor"
    ],
    "possible_false_positives": [
      "If runtime context is guaranteed single-threaded in production and setters are never interleaved, first finding impact is lower than scored.",
